@NODE Intro "Introduction to Loan"

  Loan is a program, born from necessity.  When my sister decided to buy
  a house, she wanted to see how much a loan would really cost her.
  Instead of firing up the trusty spreadsheet, I opted to write a quick
  program in 'C'.

  It was a pretty basic, boring command-line program but it did the job
  in a hurry...

  After sitting in front of the computer typing in command-line options
  for my sister I decided to bit the bullet and make it user-friendly.

  I got my hands on MUIBuilder, by Eric Totel, and started writing a
  neat little MUI program.  After a few hours of bashing away, this is
  what I came up with!

  I thought to myself, I'm going to release this stuff as freeware, 
  other people could actually use this stuff!  So I started writing a 
  doc.  Well this is my first AmigaGuide® document I've created and I'm
  pretty impressed how easy it is to create one!!

  Anyway I hope this little program can help you when you check out your
  loan, it does make it easier to choose how much you pay each time,
  you might even be surprised how much difference it makes paying weekly
  instead of fortnightly!!

  Josh Marshall.

@ENDNODE

@NODE Loan "Loan Calculator"

Loan is a very simple program to use.

@{u}The input@{uu}

  @{" Capital " link capital }
  @{" Amount per Payment " link amount }
  @{" Cycle Gadget " link Payment_rate }
  @{" Interest Rate " link rate }
  @{" Extra Payment " link xtra }
  @{" Number of Extra Payments " link xtratime }
  @{" Go Do It! " link GO }

@{u}The results@{uu}

  @{" Loan Results " link Results }

@ENDNODE

@NODE capital "Capital"
Capital is the amount of money initially borrowed from the bank.
@ENDNODE

@NODE amount "Amount per Payment"
The Amount Per Payment is the amount of money paid into the loan at regular
intervals.
@ENDNODE

@NODE Payment_rate "Cycle Gadget"
The Payment Rate is how often money is paid to the bank.

Current options are:

* Daily
* Weekly
* Fortnightly
* Monthly
* Yearly
@ENDNODE

@NODE rate "Interest Rate"
The Interest Rate is the percentage of the balance per year that the bank 
will charge you.

For example, if you have an 8% rate on a 100,000 loan, you will be charged
8,000 for that year.
@ENDNODE

@NODE xtra "Extra Payment"
Extra payments at the start of the loan are configured with this variable.

If, for example, you wish to pile more money into the loan at the start of 
the loaning period, this is how much extra you are paying (on top of normal 
re-payments)
@ENDNODE

@NODE xtratime "Number of Extra Payments"
If you are paying extra into the loan at the beginning of the period, this 
variable tells the computer how many of these larger payments will continue.
@ENDNODE

@NODE GO "Go Do It!"
Press the Go! button and you will soon find out how much you owe...
@ENDNODE

@NODE Results "Loan Results"
This window shows a heap of lines that look something like:

  Payment #  10  Capital    79453.56  Interest   100.23  Total Paid     1500.00
  ...

This shows a blow-by-blow account of how much you have paid, how much you still
owe and how much interest was added to the loan since the last payment.

Prepare for a small surprise on the "Total Paid" figure at the end!
@ENDNODE

